[[Anna Vissi]] represented '''Greece in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2006]]''' with her song "[[Everything (Anna Vissi song)|Everything]]". The Greek national broadcaster, [[Ellinik<U+00ED> Radiofon<U+00ED>a Tile<U+00F3>rasi]] (ERT), internally selected Vissi to represent the country at the contest, which took place in [[Athens]] after Greece's win at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005 contest]] with the song "[[My Number One]]" performed by [[Elena Paparizou]]. "Everything", composed by [[Nikos Karvelas]] and written by Anna Vissi herself, was selected on March 14, 2006 at a national final by a combination of a [[televoting]]/SMS vote (60%) and expert jury (40%). At Eurovision, Vissi placed 9th, receiving 128 points. 

==Background==
{{main|Greece in the Eurovision Song Contest}}
The Eurovision Song Contest 2006 marked Greece's twenty-seventh participation in the Contest since its first entry in 1974.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-year/contest?event=290|title=Eurovision Song Contest 1974 |publisher=www.eurovision.tv|accessdate=2009-01-17}}</ref> It won for the first time at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|previous contest]] in 2005 with the song "[[My Number One]]" performed by [[Elena Paparizou]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/tv_and_radio/4566149.stm|title= Eurovision win for Greek singer|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2009-01-17|last=|first= | date=2005-05-21}}
</ref> and had been placed third twice up to the Contest: in 2001 with the song "[[Die for You (Antique song)|Die for You]]"  performed by the duo [[Antique (duo)|Antique]] and in 2004 with "[[Shake It (Sakis Rouvas song)|Shake It]]"  performed by [[Sakis Rouvas]]. Following the [[Eurovision_Song_Contest#Semi-finals|introduction of semi-finals]] for the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2004|2004 contest]], Greece has had a top ten placing each year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/13610|title=Introducing the 2009 entries: Greece|last=Klier|first=Marcus|date=2009-03-30|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2009-03-30}}</ref>  Greece's least successful result was in 1998 when it placed twentieth with the song "[[Mia Krifi Evesthisia]]" by [[Thalassa]], receiving only twelve points in total, all from Cyprus.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurovision.tv/page/history/by-country/country?country=19 |title=History by Country: Greece|publisher=''[[European Broadcasting Union]]''|accessdate=2009-01-06}}</ref>

The Greek national broadcaster, [[Ellinik<U+00ED> Radiofon<U+00ED>a Tile<U+00F3>rasi]] (ERT) broadcasts the event in Greece each year and organizes the selection process for its entry.<ref>Paravantes, Maria. (2005-06-11). Joy In Greece Over Eurovision Win. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' 117(24), 17-17. Retrieved on 2009-01-16.</ref> From 2001 to 2003, ERT held a national final with several artists, but for 2004 and 2005, it selected high-profile artists internally and set up national finals to choose their song. ERT continued the internal selection of the artist for 2006 and subsequently held a national final to select the song.

==Performer==
On August 6, 2005, [[MAD TV (Greece)|MAD TV]] reported that [[Despina Vandi]] was "seriously considering" representing Greece in 2006 and would be or possibly already had been proposed to by ERT to be the Greek entrant.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/4837|title=MAD: 'ERT to ask Despina Vandi'|last=Klier|first=Marcus|date=2005-08-07|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> Vandi had been asked previously to represent the country at the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005 contest]], but declined, fearing a bad result while her international career was going well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/3406|title=ERT excludes Despina Vandi from selection|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2004-11-28|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-09-23}}</ref> A few months later on December 12, 2005, [[Star Channel]] announced that ERT would soon officially propose to a different artist, [[Anna Vissi]], to be the representative. Vissi said in reply that she "never [excludes] a Eurovision Song Contest participation as long as everything is organized well".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5259|title='Anna Vissi proposed to represent Greece'|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2005-12-13|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> She had participated in the contest twice before: in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1980|1980]] with "[[Autostop]]" for Greece and in [[Eurovision Song Contest 1982|1982]] for Cyprus with the song "[[Mono I Agapi]]", placing 13th and 5th respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/12510|title=Greece: Anna Vissi to cover Madonna|last=Psomas|first=Nicholas|date=2008-11-14|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-19}}</ref> An official announcement was not made soon after as no agreement could be made at the time, but one month later on January 24, 2006, Vissi was officially announced as the artist for 2006.<ref name="vissiofficial">{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5411|title=Hosts Greek national selection announced|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2006-01-24|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.mad.tv/news/new.php?id=20125|title=EuroVISSIon 2006 <U+03BA><U+03B1><U+03B9> <U+03B5><U+03C0><U+03B9><U+03C3><U+03AE><U+03BC><U+03C9><U+03C2>!|date=2006-01-24|publisher=''[[MAD TV (Greece)|MAD TV]]''|language=Greek|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> A few days later in an interview with the press, she said "finally [a decision is made], I want to go to Eurovision too much". She said the reason that the final decision took so long to be announced was because she was still debating entering; using opinion polls along with talking to her usual collaborators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.mad.tv/news/new.php?id=20162|title=<U+03A3><U+03C5><U+03BD><U+03AD><U+03BD><U+03C4><U+03B5><U+03C5><U+03BE><U+03B7> <U+03A4><U+03CD><U+03C0><U+03BF><U+03C5> <U+03B3><U+03B9><U+03B1> <U+03C4><U+03B7><U+03BD> Eurovision|date=2006-01-31|publisher=''[[MAD TV (Greece)|MAD TV]]''|language=Greek|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> It was also announced that the Vissi would sing either four or five songs live at the national final to choose her song.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://beta.mad.tv/news/new.php?id=20167|title=Eurovision 2006: Q&A|date=2006-02-01|publisher=''[[MAD TV (Greece)|MAD TV]]''|language=Greek|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref>

==National final==
The date of the final was set for March 14, 2006 and took place at club ''Votanikos''; broadcast live as a television program titled ''Feel the Party''.<ref name="final" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5554|title=Greece selects song on 14th March|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2006-02-10|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> The show was hosted by Giorgos Capountzides and Zeta Makripoulia from the Greek television series ''[[Sto Para Pente]]'' and included a recap of Greece's entries from 1974 to 2005.<ref name="finaltouches">{{cite web|url=http://eurovision.ert.gr/2006/en/calendar.asp?id=15922&pmonth=3&pday=13|title=Rehearsals in Votanikos  Final Touches for the Greek Final|last=Theodorou|first=Vagelis|date=2006-03-13|publisher=''[[Ellinik<U+00ED> Radiofon<U+00ED>a Tile<U+00F3>rasi]]''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5411|title=Hosts Greek national selection announced|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2006-01-19|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> Past entries such as "[[Mathima Solfege]]", "[[Stop (Bang song)|Stop]]", "[[I Anixi]]", and "[[Die for You (Antique song)|I Would Die for You]]" were shown on a large screen along with a video message by 2006 Eurovision host [[Maria Menounos]], while [[Sakis Rouvas]], [[Elena Paparizou]], and [[Nana Mouskouri]] all sent personal messages via satellite.<ref name="afterfinal">{{cite web|url=http://eurovision.ert.gr/2006/en/calendar.asp?id=15948&pmonth=3&pday=15|title="Everything" for the ESC|last=Keleri|first=Vicky|date=2006-03-15|publisher=''[[Ellinik<U+00ED> Radiofon<U+00ED>a Tile<U+00F3>rasi]]''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref><ref name="afterfinalmad">{{cite web|url=http://beta.mad.tv/news/new.php?id=20544|title="Everything" <U+03B3><U+03B9><U+03B1> <U+03C4><U+03B7><U+03BD> Eurovision!|date=2006-03-15|publisher=''[[MAD TV (Greece)|MAD TV]]''|language=Greek|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> During the show, guest acts representing other countries partaking in Eurovision performed their entries and they included: [[Fabrizio Faniello]] of Malta with "[[I Do (Fabrizio Faniello song)|I Do]]", [[Sibel Tuzun]] of Turkey with "[[S<U+00FC>per Star]]", [[Mihai Traistariu]] of Romania with "[[Torner<U+00F2>]]", [[Christine Guldbrandsen]] of Norway with "[[Alvedansen]]", and [[Annet Artani]] of Cyprus with "[[Why Angels Cry]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5784|title=Everything for Greece|last=West-Soley|first=Richard|date=2006-03-14|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref>

Four candidate songs were decided on for Vissi to sing at the national final by ERT: "Who Cares About Love" which was written and composed by [[Nikos Karvelas]], "[[Everything (Anna Vissi song)|Everything]]" which was also composed by Karvelas, with lyrics by Anna Vissi, "Welcome to the Party" which was composed by [[Dimitris Kontopoulos]] with lyrics by Dimitris S, and "A Beautiful Night" which was written and composed by Pegasos (Antonis and Dimitris Papavomvolakis).<ref name="foursongs">{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5743|title=Four songs Anna Vissi announced|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2006-03-10|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref> "Everything" is described as a ballad, while the three others are more upbeat.<ref name="final">{{cite web|url=http://esctoday.com/news/read/5777|title=Tonight: Greece selects song for Anna Vissi|last=Bakker|first=Sietse|date=2006-03-14|publisher=''ESCToday''|accessdate=2008-11-15}}</ref>

The winning song was chosen by the public through [[televoting]] and a jury weighted at 60% and 40% of the result respectively. The jury panel was made up of Mimis Plessas, Antonis Andrikakis, Dimitris Starovas, Themos Anastasiadis, Christina Politi, Evangelia Piskera, Antonis Karatzikos, Rena Kapitsala, and a ninth vote was split between Sietse Bakker of [http://esctoday.com/ ESCToday] and Fotis Konstantopoulos of [http://www.oikotimes.com/v2/ Oikotimes].<ref name="final" /><ref name="afterfinal" />

===Result of national final===
"Everything" was proclaimed the winner after receiving 47.79% of the total vote, representing over 200,000 televotes. She received 55.66% of the vote from the viewers and 35.98% from the jury. "Welcome to the Party" placed second with 26.32% (27.69% from the viewers; 24.27% from the jury), 13.72% (7.25% from the viewers; 24.43% from the jury) for "Who Cares About Love" in third place, and 12.6% (9.39% from the viewers; 16.32% from the jury) for "A Beautiful Night" which placed last. Vissi stated that she liked all four songs, and after seeing the results, pledged to sing "Everything" "from the heart and give all her best for Greece".<ref name="afterfinal" /><ref name="afterfinalmad" />

